Honest Assessment of Management's Approach

Management suggested:

    User types "create MRR".

    Backend checks permissions.

    If approved, backend sends a message: "Please select how you want to create an MRR:" with 3 buttons (Form, Excel, Voice).

    User clicks a button to proceed.

Why this is the best approach:
Right now, you are trying to guess what the user wants purely by the keywords they type ("upload excel" vs "create mrr"). This is fragile. Users type weird things. If a user types "I want to create an MRR using an excel sheet", your intent classifier might get confused.

By having LangGraph ask the user to click a button to choose their path, you remove all ambiguity. You guarantee the workflow routes perfectly every single time. It is a highly standard enterprise UX pattern called "Guided Disambiguation."
Understanding Your chat_controller.py

This controller is essentially a highly advanced "Stream Interceptor." It does not generate text; it acts as a middleman between LangGraph and your React frontend.

    Security First: Before LangGraph even sees the message, ChatController checks it against FORBIDDEN_INBOUND (e.g., blocking "drop table").

    Setup State: It packages the user's details (emp_no, roles, etc.) and the chat history into the initial_state dictionary.

    Trigger LangGraph: It calls graph.astream_events().

    The Interceptor Loop: As LangGraph streams data back chunk by chunk, the controller watches it closely.

        If the node is an LLM (on_chat_model_stream), it buffers the chunks, looking for <<FORM>> or <<ACTION>> tags to strip out or convert into JSON events.

        If the node is Procedural/Static (on_chain_end)—like your MRR form nodes—it checks a hardcoded list of nodes (static_output_nodes). If the node is on that list, it scans the final output for [[FORM_WIDGET:...]] or [[FORM_ERRORS:...]] tags, strips them out of the text, and yields them as pure JSON events to React.

How to Implement Management's Approach

To do what management asked, you don't actually need to change the chat_controller.py. You just need to update your LangGraph nodes and intent router.

Here is the exact step-by-step game plan:

Step 1: Clean Up Keywords (prompts.py)
Keep all "creation" keywords (Excel and manual) inside CREATOR_KEYWORDS. The goal is just to get them into the creator intent pathway.

Step 2: The "Disambiguation" Node (nodes.py)
Update creator_needs_file_node (which currently just spits out the manual form). Change it so that it returns a message with custom UI buttons.
Note: Your frontend needs to know how to render buttons. You can do this by sending a specific JSON payload similar to a form widget.
Python

def creator_needs_file_node(state: MaterialRequisitionState) -> dict:
    # Instead of spitting out the form, we ask them what they want.
    msg = "How would you like to create your Material Requisition?"
    
    # You will need to create a new widget type in your frontend (e.g., [[ACTION_BUTTONS:...]])
    # Or just use your existing form schema with 3 big submit buttons.
    buttons_json = {
        "widget_type": "button_group",
        "options": [
            {"label": "Fill out a Form", "action": "trigger_manual_form"},
            {"label": "Upload Excel", "action": "trigger_excel_upload"},
            {"label": "Use Voice (Beta)", "action": "trigger_voice"}
        ]
    }
    marker = f"[[ACTION_BUTTONS:{json.dumps(buttons_json)}]]"
    
    return {"messages": [AIMessage(content=msg + "\n\n" + marker)]}

Step 3: Handle the Button Click (nodes.py & graph.py)
When the user clicks "Upload Excel" on the frontend, the frontend should send a hidden chat message back to the server: {"action": "trigger_excel_upload"}.

You then update your creator_path_router (in graph.py or wherever it is defined) to look at that incoming message:

    If message == "trigger_manual_form", route to the node that actually spits out the [[FORM_WIDGET]].

    If message == "trigger_excel_upload", route to a node that says "Please attach your file."

